<section id="methods">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div>
        <div class="kicker">Method and robustness</div>
        <h2>The analytic pipeline in five steps.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>Editors and reviewers should be able to understand the pipeline in one pass, then inspect the pieces that support credibility.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="methods-grid">
      <div class="panel methods-left">
        <h3>Five-step analytic flow</h3>
        <div class="steps">
          <div class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Phase-stratified repeated cross-sections</h4>
              <p>The data are organized into five pandemic phases rather than treated as one undifferentiated pool. This turns the paper into a comparative systems study: the same source population is sampled repeatedly across changing macro conditions, allowing structured phase-wise contrasts while avoiding false longitudinal claims.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Graphical model estimation</h4>
              <p>For each phase, the symptom network is estimated with a Gaussian graphical model using graphical LASSO. The resulting graph represents conditional dependence structure among 47 MHQ symptoms, providing the support on which community and domination analyses are built.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Community detection and domain alignment</h4>
              <p>Weighted Louvain community detection identifies a small number of phase-specific communities. These are then aligned to a fixed, a priori domain mapping to make cross-phase interpretation comparable and non-circular.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Exact minimum dominating sets and control metrics</h4>
              <p>All minimum-cardinality dominating sets are enumerated exactly on the unweighted support graph. This allows defining node-level control frequency and deriving module-level measures such as ACF and AMCS rather than relying only on traditional hub metrics.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">5</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Resampling, case-dropping, and replication</h4>
              <p>The study explicitly asks which metrics survive bootstrap variation and case loss, then checks whether the broad mesoscale story replicates in an India cohort, including phase-wise downsampling to control for sample-size differences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="panel methods-right">
        <h3>Evidence of rigor</h3>
        <div class="evidence-cards">
          <div class="evidence-card">
            <h4>Replication</h4>
            <p>India cohort replication and phase-wise downsampling sensitivity analysis help show that the mesoscale and control-redistribution patterns are not a simple artifact of one country or a larger comparison sample.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="evidence-card">
            <h4>Metric discipline</h4>
            <p>Node strength and AMCS are elevated as the more stable signals, while ACF is explicitly presented as a descriptive metric that is more case-loss sensitive.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="evidence-card">
            <h4>Bounded inference</h4>
            <p>The design is repeated cross-sectional, not longitudinal; network edges are conditional dependencies, not causal directions; and macro links are exploratory.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="robustness-bars">
          <h4>Stability at 60% case retention</h4>
          <p class="bar-subtitle">Mean replicate-to-baseline correlation across phases</p>
          <div class="bar-row">
            <span class="bar-label">Strength</span>
            <div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill bar-good" style="width: 83.8%"></div></div>
            <span class="bar-value">0.838</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-row">
            <span class="bar-label">AMCS</span>
            <div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill bar-moderate" style="width: 73.7%"></div></div>
            <span class="bar-value">0.737</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-row">
            <span class="bar-label">ACF</span>
            <div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill bar-weak" style="width: 33.9%"></div></div>
            <span class="bar-value">0.339</span>
          </div>
          <p class="bar-note">This hierarchy explains why the manuscript emphasizes some metrics more than others.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

